{{Infobox person | name = Alfred Peet | image = Alfred Peet.jpg | caption = Peet in the late 1960s at the original Peet's location | birth_date = {{Birth date|1920|3|10}} | birth_place = [[Alkmaar]], The [[Netherlands]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2007|8|29|1920|3|20}} | death_place = [[Ashland, Oregon]], [[United States|U.S.]] | occupation = [[Entrepreneur|Founder]] of [[Peet's Coffee & Tea]] }}
'''Alfred H. Peet''' (March 10, 1920 &ndash; August 29, 2007) was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]]-[[United States|American]] entrepreneur and the founder of [[Peet's Coffee & Tea]] in [[Berkeley, California]], in 1966. He is most famous for introducing custom [[coffee]] roasting to the United States using top quality beans at a time when Americans were typically drinking coffee that came out of a can.{{what|date=May 2018}}<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/03/us/03peet.html?_r=0 Alfred H. Peet, 87, Dies; Leader of a Coffee Revolution, by Carolyn Marshall, September 3, 2007]</ref> Peet taught his style of roasting beans to [[Jerry Baldwin]], [[Zev Siegl]] and [[Gordon Bowker]], who took the technique to [[Seattle]] and founded [[Starbucks]] in 1971. Peet is widely credited with starting the specialty coffee revolution in the US. Among coffee historians, Peet is labeled as "the Dutchman who taught America how to drink coffee."<ref name="NOS" />
==Life and career== Peet was born in [[Alkmaar]], The [[Netherlands]], where his father ran a small coffee roastery before [[World War II]].<ref name=cvbt>{{cite web | url=http://www.centralvalleybusinesstimes.com/stories/001/?ID=6166 | title=Coffee pioneer Peet dies | date=31 August 2007 | accessdate=2007-08-31 | work=Central Valley Business Times | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929063236/http://www.centralvalleybusinesstimes.com/stories/001/?ID=6166 | archivedate=2007-09-29 | deadurl=yes | df= }}</ref> After the war, Peet left London, where he had apprenticed with a coffee and tea company, and worked as a [[Tea tasting|tea taster]] in the [[Dutch East Indies]] and [[New Zealand]] before [[emigrate|emigrating]] to [[San Francisco, California]], in 1955, where he worked in the coffee importing industry.<ref name=sfsen>{{cite news | url=http://www.sanfranciscosentinel.com/?p=4524 | title=The passing of Al Peet—the founder of Peet's Coffee | date=August 31, 2007 | accessdate=2007-08-31 | last=Murphy | first=Pat | work=San Francisco Sentinel| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070902101032/http://www.sanfranciscosentinel.com/?p=4524| archivedate= 2 September 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref name=mailtrib>{{cite news | url=http://archive.mailtribune.com/archive/2003/0601/local/stories/03local.htm | title=Peet now calls Medford his home | date=2003-06-01 | last=Stiles | first=Greg | work=Mail-Tribune | accessdate=2007-08-31| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070929092847/http://archive.mailtribune.com/archive/2003/0601/local/stories/03local.htm| archivedate= 29 September 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
After becoming dismayed at the poor quality of coffee in the United States (according to Peet, the reason that the quality of coffee was so bad in the USA is that people were still drinking World War II style "rationed" coffee),<ref name="NOS">{{cite web|title=Nederlander leerde Amerika koffie drinken |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/64234-nederlander-leerde-amerika-koffie-drinken.html |website=NOS Nieuws |accessdate=9 October 2016 |date=2007-09-04 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929222917/http://nos.nl/artikel/64234-nederlander-leerde-amerika-koffie-drinken.html |archivedate=29 September 2012 |df= }} (in Dutch).</ref> he opened his own coffee store in [[Berkeley, California]], in 1966. Although often encouraged to expand the business, he remained stalwart in keeping the single location at Walnut and Vine and zealously guarding the quality of the coffee bearing his name.
Peet sold the business in 1979 to Sal Bonavita and remained a mentor and teacher to Sal for the next five years. Bonavita soon opened new stores in [[Oakland, California|Oakland]], [[Mill Valley, California|Mill Valley]] and [[Menlo Park, California|Menlo Park]].<ref>{{cite news | work=San Francisco Chronicle | title=Coffee pioneer Alfred Peet dies | author=George Raine | date=2007-09-01 | url=http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/09/01/BUEIRTFAV.DTL | accessdate=2007-09-01}}</ref>
An interview with Alfred Peet is included in the documentary "Coffee Culture USA" released in 2008.
After retiring from the coffee business, Peet moved in 2001 to [[Ashland, Oregon]], where he died on August 29, 2007, at age 87.<ref name="Marshall2007">{{cite news|author1=Marshall, Carolyn |author2=Severson, Kim |title=Alfred H. Peet, 87, Dies; Leader of a Coffee Revolution|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/03/us/03peet.html|accessdate=5 October 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=2007-09-03|page=B5}}</ref><ref name=oreg>{{cite news | url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/breakingnews/2007/08/founder_of_peets_coffee_dies_a.html | title=Founder of Peet's Coffee dies at home in Ashland | work=The Oregonian | date=2007-08-31 |accessdate=2007-08-31| archiveurl= https://archive.is/20070917090300/http://blog.oregonlive.com/breakingnews/2007/08/founder_of_peets_coffee_dies_a.html| archivedate= 17 September 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
