{{use mdy dates|date=November 2016}} {{ Infobox officeholder |name = Gianroberto Casaleggio |image = Gianroberto Casaleggio 23 maggio 2014 2.jpg |caption = |office = Co-founder of the [[Five Star Movement]] |alongside = [[Beppe Grillo]] |term_start = 4 October 2009 |term_end = 12 April 2016 |predecessor = |successor2 = |birth_name = Gianroberto Casaleggio |birth_date = {{birth date|1954|8|14|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Milan]], Italy |death_date = {{death date and age|2016|4|12|1954|8|14|df=y}} |death_place = [[Milan]], Italy |death_cause = [[Brain cancer]] |resting_place = |resting_place_coordinates = |nationality = |party = [[Five Star Movement]] |spouse = |children = 2 |residence = |alma_mater = |occupation = {{Hlist|[[Activist]]|[[entrepreneur]]}} |profession = |religion = |signature = |website = [http://www.beppegrillo.it beppegrillo.it] |footnotes = }}
'''Gianroberto Casaleggio''' ({{IPA-it|dʒanroˈbɛrto kazaˈleddʒo}}; 14 August 1954 – 12 April 2016) was an Italian entrepreneur and [[political activist]], born in [[Milan]].
He was co-founder and [[chairman]] of Casaleggio Associati srl, an internet and publishing company that advises on network strategies, and editor of Beppe Grillo's blog. He was also co-founder, with [[Beppe Grillo]], of the [[Five Star Movement]], of which he was sometimes called "[[guru]]".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2012/05/26/italia/politica/grillo-e-l-ombra-di-casaleggioil-guru-con-il-mito-di-re-artu-HTkcdZOw3zpCfJ13VuQXYL/pagina.html|title=Grillo e l’ombra di Casaleggio il guru con il mito di Re Artù|newspaper=''[[La Stampa]]''|author=Marco Alfieri|date=26 May 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2012/09/08/guru-casaleggio-esce-dallombra-non-decido-io/346592/|title=Il guru Casaleggio esce dall’ombra: "Non decido io"|newspaper=''il Fatto Quotidiano''|author=Emiliano Liuzzi|date=8 September 2012|accessdate=20 December 2012|language=it}}</ref> In the Italian context, Casaleggio promoted the [[World Wide Web|Web]] as a medium for political communication.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Natale|first=Simone|last2=Ballatore|first2=Andrea|date=2014-01-01|title=The web will kill them all: new media, digital utopia, and political struggle in the Italian 5-Star Movement|url=http://mcs.sagepub.com/content/36/1/105|journal=Media, Culture & Society|language=en|volume=36|issue=1|pages=105–121|doi=10.1177/0163443713511902|issn=0163-4437}}</ref>
==Biography== Casaleggio began his career working at [[Olivetti|Olivetti S.p.A]], then, in the late 1990s, became CEO at Webegg SpA, an internet consulting company. Webegg suffered heavy losses (over €20 million) in the period 2002–2003, and Casaleggio was replaced as CEO of Webegg in 2003 by Giuseppe Longo, appointed to lead the company turnaround.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.milanofinanza.it/giornali/preview_giornali.asp?id=1113780&codiciTestate=7&sez=giornali&testo=italia&titolo=Telecom%20Italia%20rinuncia%20al%20controllo%20di%20Webegg|title=Telecom Italia rinuncia al controllo di Webegg|newspaper=MF Milano Finanza|date=6 April 2004|language=it}}</ref> In 2004, Casaleggio founded '''Casaleggio Associati''', an internet consulting company that carries out research on e-commerce in Italy and whose finding are presented at a conference held in Milan every spring (since 2006).
Casaleggio Associati has been since 2005 the editor of Beppe Grillo's blog as well as of some of Grillo's books. Casaleggio Associati was also editor of the web-blog of [[Antonio Di Pietro]] (until 2010),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ilmessaggero.it/primopiano/politica/grillo_di_pietro_idv_ingroia_elezioni/notizie/229338.shtml|title=Grillo-Di Pietro, il piano per le elezioni"Ingroia candidato premier"|author=Ettore Colombo|newspaper=''[[Il Messaggero]]''|date=3 November 2012|accessdate=5 November 2012|language=it}}</ref> and the website of Chiarelettere, an editor, until 2013, when was dismissed following divergence over the editorial strategy.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.vanityfair.it/news/italia/13/07-%281%29/08/casaleggio-grillo-chiarelettere-fatto-quotidiano-cadoinpiedi|title = Il guru dimezzato|newspaper = [[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|author = Francesco Oggiano|date = 8 July 2013|accessdate = 8 July 2013|language = it|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130712033600/http://www.vanityfair.it/news/italia/13/07-(1)/08/casaleggio-grillo-chiarelettere-fatto-quotidiano-cadoinpiedi|archivedate = July 12, 2013|df = mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ilgiornale.it/news/interni/quando-travaglio-c-mandarono-quel-paese-guru-cinque-stelle-854855.html|title=Quando Travaglio & C. mandarono a quel paese il guru a cinque stelle|newspaper=il Giornale|author=Paolo Bracalini|date=12 November 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|language=it}}</ref>
Gianroberto Casaleggio died on 12 April 2016 in Milan, at the age of 61, after a long period of illness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corriere.it/politica/16_aprile_12/m5s-morto-gianroberto-casaleggio-628f6308-0088-11e6-8701-d21ef4c79bc6.shtml|title=M5s, è morto Gianroberto Casaleggio Fotostoria{{!}} Le frasi {{!}} I video|accessdate=14 November 2016|work=[[Corriere della Sera|Corriere.it]]|language=it}}</ref>
==Family== After Gianroberto's death, his son [[Davide Casaleggio|Davide]] was appointed to replace him as president of Casaleggio Associati.<ref>Horowitz, Jason, [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/12/world/europe/with-success-comes-dissension-in-italys-five-star-movement.html "With Success Comes Dissension in Italy’s Five Star Movement"], ''[[New York Times]]'', December 12, 2016. Retrieved 2016-12-12.</ref>
